🏞️Want to keep Earth Healthy?⬇️

Incredible landscapes and healthy environments are something that we often take for granted. But we can learn a lot about protecting these spaces and many more natural ecosystems around the world by learning from Indigenous Peoples!

Supporting Indigenous Peoples’ rights is the best way to protect our Earth’s health. A healthy earth plays an important role in our health.

Indigenous Peoples globally hold ancestral knowledge relevant to our whole world that is deeply important for health and environmental causes. 

That’s why I’ve partnered with The Global Alliance of Territorial Communities! They’re a coordinating body of indigenous peoples and local communities from 25 countries around the world! 

One of the excellent examples is the Embera People who live in Panama.

Some knowledge that the Embera people and their leader Omayra Cosama shared with me:

• Learn to sync to the rhythms of nature and the natural seasons of the planet; The Embera people are taught to connect with nature from early childhood!
• Be careful not to over exploit the Earth. We only have one.
• Consider natural, plant based medicines. Remember that if we protect nature, we will have more of these natural medicines around when we need them.

International Day of the World’s Indigenous Peoples is a day we can come together to commemorate the timeless heritage and traditional knowledge that indigenous communities provide! 

How you can play a part:
• By allying with Indigenous Peoples whenever you see opportunity in conversations
• Follow the Global Alliance of Territorial Communities IG account @globalalliancet
• Share their messages to garner global solidarity with Indigenous Peoples.

📝 My whole life, I’ve felt like I probably wouldn’t go very far. Even after traveling for years now, it’s hard to believe that someone like me could make it to these places. I was no one. Just a kid that their parents didn’t want. Fortunate enough to be adopted by my grandma, but deep down I think I still felt pretty unworthy of anything big. But the truth is, you can do anything. The biggest thing holding you back is believing it. 🫶

📍 Moraine Lake, Banff National Park, Canada 
One of the most photographed lakes in the world, it truly is a scene right out of a dream. Looking at it, it’s hard to believe what you’re seeing. It’s very regulated now, so you can’t park here. You’ll need to either win the lottery for the public shuttle bus or hire a private shuttle. You can also opt to stay at the lodge, but it’s not really in the budget range of most people (it can cost close to 4 figures for a single night). I was thankful to get the sunrise shuttle and be able to see this place at first light! It was completely worth the 3 AM wake-up call.

🌎 So, where to next?

I’ll never forget this view 🤯 

Share this if you’re a subset junkie! 😊

Last time we did this hike, we got totally skunked with such thick fog you couldn’t see anything! Literally beyond your hands in front of you, it was a white out.

This time, we returned but the base of the climb was not looking good but we decided to try anyway. Just the drive to the trailhead took hours so even a chance was worth it! 

As we made it to the summit we saw an epic cloud inversion and finally at the fire lookout an Mt. rainier was showing off! 

If you’re heading to Mt. Rainier, just know it is really common for the peak to be covered in clouds so these conditions were such a treat!

This message helped change my life 🥹

Follow along if you want to live life to the fullest, to use every second of the life you have here to do something incredible. Please don’t waste it!

Before my life became what you see in these videos, I was working in corporate. Just when I was a few months from completing my residency as an engineer, there was a pivotal moment. You see, I didn’t grow up with any money, and I was convinced that becoming an engineer meant that I had made it. 

But I hated what I was doing. I felt lifeless. It was the hardest time to leave, because everyone was telling me I had achieved “success.” The dream job. Was this my life for the next 40 years? I was shaking and sweating when I handed in my resignation. 

I had no idea what I was going to do. I thought the next step was to start my own business. I wanted to build something that was really mine. So for the next 4 years I worked 7 days a week, often 60-80 hour weeks. And I became “successful” again. But I burnt out. I couldn’t do it anymore.

Then I found travel. I found hiking. Exploring. I found instagram and content creation. I started to build a community here. And I found all of you. I still can’t believe there are 400,000 of you following along. 🤯 I’m thankful to have you here and to continue to grow this. Without your support, I couldn’t do this and I genuinely appreciate all of you who are a part of my journey!

I’d love you to share some of your stories, struggles, or successes below! 

👋 If you’re new to my page, you’re welcome to come be a part of whatever it is I’m doing next. No guarantees at what it will be, only that it will be a wild ride!

I love getting messages from y’all telling me I’ve inspired you or you’ve gone crazy and bought a camper and you’re doing the things! It means so much to me to know I could help change someone’s life!

I’ve been telling my story on here piece by piece. I didn’t mention my parents for probably a year after starting this account because I didn’t want to talk about it publicly (or at all, really). 

But so many of you related to it and I hope it inspires you and reminds you that life is short. Don’t let it slip away. Go on an adventure. Take that trip you’ve been dreaming of. Chase after your dreams. Worst case scenario is you can probably go back to living how you are now.

But what if it all works out?

Cheers,

Dalt

🥾🥾🥾 How to Get to Tolmie Peak Trailhead:
Drive to the Mowich Lake Trailhead, the starting point for the Tolmie Peak trail. The trail begins near the lake.

⏰ How Long is the Tolmie Peak Hike?
The hike to Tolmie Peak typically takes around 3-4 hours, covering approximately 6.5 miles roundtrip. Allow extra time for breaks and enjoying the breathtaking views.

📝 Do I Need a Permit to Hike Tolmie Peak?
No permit is required for day hiking. However, if you plan an overnight trip, check with the park for permit requirements.

🎽 What Should I Wear for Hiking Tolmie Peak?
Dress in layers suitable for the weather. Sturdy hiking boots are essential, and consider bringing a rain jacket as the weather in the mountains can be unpredictable. I would also consider trekking poles!

📅 Best Time of Year to Hike Tolmie Peak?
Late spring to early fall is ideal for hiking Tolmie Peak. Be prepared for snow at higher elevations in early and late season.

⚠️ Check weather conditions and park alerts before embarking on the hike.

🗺️ Are Guided Tours Available for Tolmie Peak?
Typically this is a self guided hike. Don’t worry, there are usually plenty of other hikers along the way!

🥾 What Other Hikes Should I Do in Mt. Rainier National Park?
For more adventure, try the Skyline Trail for a closer look at Mt. Rainier. For experienced hikers, the Wonderland Trail offers a multi-day trek around the mountain.

🏕️ Where Should I Stay?
If camping, consider Mowich Lake Campground. For a more comfortable stay, lodging in Enumclaw or Buckley is recommended.

Why you NEED to prioritize getting outside! 👇

🥾Today is National Take a Hike Day and I’ve been thinking lately about how not everyone can make it to bucket list national parks or the “epic hiking destinations” that you often see on your feed. 

But the truth is, everyone needs time outside. 

There are so many benefits for your physical AND mental health. It might sound crazy, but just the sound of water flowing, wind blowing through the trees, or a little time in a hammock in the forest can make a huge difference in my day. 

Here are a few reasons why I get outside:

😌 Mental Health: Time outdoors can help reduce stress, anxiety, and depression
💪🏻 Physical Fitness: Move your body, it will thank you later
🌞 Vitamin D: One of the most natural ways to get it
🏞️ Environmental Awareness
😴 Sleep Quality: We all deserve good sleep, and hiking regularly can actually help

So I decided to take my new Merrell hiking boots out to some local parks to break them in, because the benefits of being outside in nature don’t have to be super far from home!

I got the Moab 3 Mid Waterproof boots, and these are seriously the most comfortable boots I’ve worn and they have great ankle support without being too heavy! 👌🏻

I’ve field tested these on multiple trails to make sure the waterproofing is solid, plus they have Vibram soles so I can step confidently when crossing streams or slippery terrain.

My first pair of hiking shoes as an adult was a pair of Merrell Amphibians that lasted me for YEARS, so I’m confident these are going to hold up just as well!

Between the stream crossings, stunning foliage, PB + Honey Banana sandwich, and time in the hammock with some hot tea, I think it’s safe to say good things come to those who hike.

SAVE this guide ⬇️

The Ultimate Guide to Hiking the Enchantments in the Alpine Lakes Wilderness

Share it with someone you’d go with! 🙌

🥾🥾🥾 How to Get to the Enchantments Trailhead:
Drive to the Stuart Lake Trailhead or the Snow Lakes Trailhead. Parking is limited, so consider carpooling.

⏰ How Long Does it Take to Hike the Enchantments?
The Enchantments hike is a very challenging 20+ mile trek that typically takes 2 to 3 days to complete. Allow extra time for breathtaking views and photo stops.

📝 Do I Need a Permit to Hike the Enchantments?
Yes, a permit is required for all overnight stays between May 15 and October 31. The permit is obtained through an EXTREMELY high demand lottery system, so plan in advance. Only 6% of the 40,000+ applicants win.

🎽 What Should I Wear for Hiking the Enchantments?
Dress in layers suitable for alpine conditions. UPF clothing, a rain shell, & hiking boots are crucial.

🎒 Where Can I Rent Gear for Hiking the Enchantments?
You can purchase gear in the town of Leavenworth. Essentials include a pack, water purification system, trekking poles, and a light tent if you’re backpacking.

🏊‍♀️ Can I Hike the Enchantments if I Can’t Swim?
Swimming is not required to complete the hike. The trail passes by crystal-clear lakes and stunning mountains. I love swimming in alpine lakes, but it is chilly throughout the year.

📅 Best Time of Year to Hike the Enchantments?
Late spring to early fall. Snow may be present in early and late season.

⚠️ Check weather conditions and trail alerts.

🗺️ Are Guided Tours Available for the Enchantments?
The Enchantments are self guided.

🥾 What Other Hikes Should I Do in Alpine Lakes Wilderness?
Colchuk or Lake Ingalls are popular options. There are 700 alpine lakes in the area!

🏨 Where Should I Stay?
Leavenworth is a great base!

Want to visit Moraine Lake?👇

📝 Save this for your bucket list!

📅 Best Time to Visit Moraine Lake? Late June to early September when the lake is most vibrant, showcasing stunning turquoise waters surrounded by majestic mountain peaks. 🏔️

✈️ Where should I fly in for Banff? Calgary International Airport (YYC) in Alberta, Canada

🏞️ How do I get to Banff National Park from YYC? You have 2 main options. A private shuttle (~ $80 each way). I suggest renting a car for a scenic road trip through the Canadian Rockies. The journey itself is an adventure, with jaw-dropping landscapes along the way.

🚗 How do I get to Moraine Lake? There are 3 ways you can get to Moraine Lake since it is closed to personal vehicles now.

 🚌Take a public or private shuttle: Parks Canada shuttle bus (reservations required) or Roam Public transit. Private shuttles cost more, but some allow you to see sunrise.

🚲 Bike to Moraine Lake (~ 24 km / 15 miles round trip), and immerse yourself in the stunning surroundings along the way!

🏨 Stay at the Moraine Lake Lodge for around $1,000 per night. Expensive, yes; but this will guarantee you access to Moraine Lake and is a great way to spend a lot of time there without a lot of hassle. If this is in your budget, DM me I’d like to come with. 😂

🥾Don’t miss the iconic Rockpile Trail, which rewards you with a panoramic view that will leave you speechless. I highly recommend Larch Valley to Sentinel Pass as well.

🛶 Consider renting a canoe. It’s a bucket list experience, bring your wallet. 

☀️ Weather Conditions: Be prepared for changing weather. Wear a wind/rain layer and pack sunscreen! ☔

📸 Photography: Arrive early in the morning or late in the evening for the best lighting, calmer water for reflections, and fewer crowds.

💰Daily entry is $10.50 the Discover Pass is $72.25
